      "FacilityID": 1000084993,
      "SummaryText": "This document presents the Halifax County Service Authority's Leigh Street Water Treatment Facility strategy to comply with the Clean Air Act requirements of Section 112(r)(7), Accidental Release Prevention Requirements: Risk Management Program.  It is the Halifax County Service Authority's  intent to enforce the policies and procedures presented in this document to prevent accidental releases of regulated substances or reduce the severity of those releases that do occur.\r\n\r\n1.0  POLICIES IN PLACE \r\n\r\nThe Leigh Street Water Treatment Facility complies with Clean Air Act and Occupation Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) air emissions regulations and has policies in place to ensure continued compliance.\r\n\r\n2.0  SOURCE AND SUBSTANCES \r\n\r\nThe facility is responsible for treating water for the Halifax County Service Authority(SIC Code 4941, NAICS 22131). Chlorine (Chemical Abstracts Services, CAS Number 7782-50-5) is used to disinfect treated water prior to distribution. The Halifax County Service Authority stores approximately four (4) 1-ton cylinders on site. \r\n\r\n3.0  PURPOSE OF RMP SUBMISSION\r\n\r\nThe RMP was initially prepared and submitted in June 1999.  The purpose of this RMP submission is to comply with the 5-year re-submission requirement as imposed by the EPA.  New information that is required for this submission is also included in this RMP.\r\n\r\n4.0  ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM \r\nThe facility is in compliance with the OSHA Process Safety Management (PSM) rule and, with this document, the Clean Air Act Accidental Release Prevention Program regulations.  The Leigh Street Water Treatment Facility relies on a system of equipment maintenance and periodic testing to prevent accidental releases. \r\n\r\n5.0  ACCIDENT HISTORY \r\nTo date, the Leigh Street Water Treatment Facility has had no accidental releases of chlorine.\r\n\r\n6.0  EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM \r\n\r\nThe Leigh Street Water Treatment Facility does not have an emergency response plan which has been coor"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000084993,
      "SummaryText": "dinated with community emergency responders.  The facility relies entirely on local community emergency response teams to address releases.\r\n\r\n7.0  PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY \r\n\r\nThe Leigh Street Water Treatment Facility has an ongoing maintenance training and operational training program to continuously update operator knowledge of systems within their facility."
    }
